  "feesApplyText": "Tenant Fees for Assured Periodic Tenancies<br />The following sets out the payments chargeable to the Tenant(s) in connection with assured periodic tenancies with an annual rent of less than \u00a3100,000 arranged by Coldwell Banker Southbank, in accordance with the Tenant Fees Act 2019 (as amended by the Renters  Rights Act 2025).<br /><br />The Rent - The agreed monthly rent as stated in the tenancy agreement. Landlords and agents are prohibited from requesting, encouraging or accepting any offer above the advertised asking rent.<br />Tenancy Deposit - A refundable tenancy deposit capped at no more than five weeks  rent where the annual rent is less than \u00a350,000, or six weeks  rent where the annual rent is \u00a350,000 or above.<br />Holding Deposit - A refundable holding deposit to reserve a property, capped at no more than one week s rent.<br />Changes to a Tenancy - If the Tenant requests a change to the tenancy agreement after the tenancy has commenced and the Landlord agrees, a charge of \u00a350 (including VAT) will apply. If additional reasonable costs are incurred (for example, in obtaining permissions from a third party), these costs will be passed on to the Tenant, provided they are evidenced as reasonable.<br />Utilities and Council Tax - Payments in respect of utilities, communication services, TV licence and council tax remain the Tenant s responsibility as set out in the tenancy agreement.<br />Key Replacement - If keys, fobs or other security devices are lost or damaged by the Tenant and require replacement, the Tenant will be liable for the reasonable costs of replacement.<br />Late Payment - Interest will be charged at 3% above the Bank of England base rate on any rent payment that has been more than 14 days overdue, calculated daily for each day the payment remains outstanding.<br />Early Termination - All tenancies arranged by Coldwell Banker Southbank are assured periodic tenancies under the Renters  Rights Act 2025. The Tenant may end the tenancy by giving two months  written notice at any time. If the Tenant vacates before the expiry of the notice period, they may be liable for rent until the earlier of: (i) the end of the notice period, or (ii) the date a suitable replacement tenant is found (subject to the Landlord s duty to mitigate loss). Any other reasonable losses incurred by the Landlord as a result may also be recoverable.<br />Contractual Damages - In the event that the Landlord incurs reasonable costs due to the Tenant s breach of contract or failure to fulfil their obligations under the tenancy agreement, the Tenant will be liable for those costs.<br />Charges correct as at May 2026. Subject to change in accordance with current legislation.<br />Client Money Protection is provided by ARLA Propertymark. Certificate number C0133964. <br />Redress Scheme: The Property Ombudsman Scheme. Membership No: D13039-0.",
